Added system user login and registrationQuick and dirty solution (for now) pulled from http://php-login-script.com/, separated from the rest of the app in the /u/ directory.n

User registration and login; Twitter account association and management.Lots of changes here:n- new classes to support owners table and owner_instances tablen- breakdown of the TwitterAPIAccessor class for access from the webappn- added the ability to add Twttter credentials to your accountn- encrypting passwords stored in the database (this could be better, but it's an improvement on what we had)n- started rudimentary access privileges mechanisms; i.e., a system user without rights to see another Twitter users's data gets bouncedn
User registration data model added; Removed is_retweet and is_followfriday from tweets table.
Set default value for instances.last_status_id to 0 instead of null
Various webapp fixes
Fixed links to login and registration
Bugfixes
Fixed broken link
Added average replies per day and other UI tweaks

Crawler and webapp bugfixes and enhancements.- Crawler: Fixed some PHP errors/notices, no more fatal error on getName() methodn- Crawler: Saves users immediately instead of queuing them for later (when job is killed prematurely)n- Crawler: Fetches followers by IDs when archive is loaded using paging mechanismn- Crawler: Fetches users one by one based on IDsn- Crawler: Records errors when user accounts have been suspendedn- Crawler: Fetches all tweet ids listed in the in_reply_to_status_id columnn- Webapp: Fixed handling of accounts without any tweets postedn
Added support for error messages (for suspended user accounts)

Added support for tweet and user retrieval error recording and tweet source.- Webapp now displays # of suspended follower accountsn- Crawler doesn't recrawl statuses or users who issued an error (like a 404 or 403)n- Tweet and User errors are now user-specific, ie, if one Twitter name doesn't have access to a user's protected updates, it doesn't change another user's ability to access those updates if that user has rights to them.n- Logger improvements: API reset time now in sync with log time, easier to read (no longer GMT)n- Switched from XML from JSON for API status call to standardize, all API calls now XML-basedn
Removed note about putting Twitter uname and pw in the config.inc.php file (no longer necessary); expounded on the warning.
Added link to Twitter's security practices documentation re: usernames and passwords.
Adjusted how follower percentage loaded is displayed and prioritized
Configure git to ignore compiled templates and smarty directory

Various crawler enhancements and bug fixes.crawl.phpn- Reordered data type priority. Now the crawler fetches:n1. Owner detailsn2. Owner tweetsn3. Owner repliesn4. Owner friendsn5. Owner followersn6. Owner replied-to tweetsn7. Unloaded followersnnCrawler class:n- Force move on if no new tweets are coming in; Twitter doesn't always return the same number of tweets for a given user it reports it hasn- Fetches followers by IDs when total number in system doesn't match reported number (no more 2% rule)n- Removed some logging for brevitynnOwnerInstance class:n- Get the oldest OAuth keys stored therennCrawlerTwitterAPIAccessorOAuth class:n- Now adjusts crawler call allowance based on how much time is left in the hour till the next reset, defaults to leaving 1 call for every minute left in the hourn- Logs more detailed info about Twitter API call account balancen

[DB MIGRATION RECOMMENDED] Issue #157: Refactored all code for ThinkTank to ThinkUp renameThis commit has far-reaching implications. Notes:nnThe $THINKTANK_CFG array in the config file is now $THINKUP_CFG. Update your thinkup/config.inc.php file accordingly. If you don't, neither the webapp nor the crawler will work.nnIf you are using the crawler cron script in thinkup/extras/cron/cron, be sure to update the config file to use the renamed variables as specified in config.sample.nnThe default database table prefix has been changed from tt_ to tu_. Run the 7/30 database migration to rename your tables, then update your thinkup/config.inc.php. This is optional, but there's an advantage to making this change now; all future migrations will assume you're using the new default table prefix, tu_.n

[DB MIGRATION REQ'D] Issue #411: Deactivate user accounts after 10 failed login attempts * To help avoid brute force password-guessing attempts, deactivate ThinkUp user accounts after 10 failed login attempts * Added 2 new fields to owners table, failed_logins and account_status * On each failed login attempt, increment the failed_logins field. On successful login, set it to 0 * If failed_logins is greater than 10, deactivate the account * Once account is deactivated, reactivate by sending an email-based password reset link (same logic as Forgot Password flow)

Issue #497: Added debug mode to Logger * Added Logger::logDebug method which writes to log only when THINKUP_CFG['debug'] = true * Added a couple debug-level messages to the Twitter crawler * Docblocks and style tweaks

Issue #502: Tests README updates and corrections * Added a warning about data loss that hopefully will stop some folks from destroying their data when running tests * Corrected example integration test name (all were renamed to WebTestOf) * Moved bit about how to run an individual test up to Running Tests section

Issue #503: Fix testing mechanisms that depend on environment variables * If the php.ini isn't configured a certain way, the $_ENV array may not be set: http://us.php.net/manual/en/ini.core.php#ini.variables-order If variables_order is set to 'SP' then PHP will create the superglobals $SERVER and $POST, but not create $ENV, $GET, and $COOKIE. * However, getenv() will always work. So for the two mechanisms that use environment variables (running single tests and printing debug statements), we use getenv instead of referencing the $_ENV array directly * Also fixed a typo and tests README.md formatting problem

[DB MIGRATION REQ'D] Reduce Twitter API 502 errors with smaller payload count argument Lowering the tweet count getting returned by the API reduces 502 errors from the Twitter API http://groups.google.com/group/twitter-development-talk/browse_thread/thread/ff498388d09b674a?pli=1 ThinkUp's default count is now 100 instead of 200. This will require more calls, but will result in fewer errors. The count is configurable in advanced options. Also configurable in advanced options: the number of API calls to leave unmade per minute remaining in the hour till your balance is reset. This field was moved from tu_instances to tu_options. Crawler bugfix * The XML parser returned a SimpleXMLElement string 'true' or 'false.' When PDO bound the string 'true' to the is_protected field (tinyint), it evaluated it to 0. This means protected author's posts were potentially being marked public in the tu_posts table. This fix casts 'true' and 'false' to 1 and 0 correctly in the XML parser and adds tests for private and public posts/users. * Sets all addPost calls in the Facebook and Twitter crawlers to use 1 or 0 for the is_protected value and tests for the correct is_protected status. * Includes a SQL migration to back-protect all posts by protected authors which are listed as public.

[DB MIGRATION REQ'D] Issue #667: Display more accurate retweet counts Prior to this patch, for new-style RTs, ThinkUp only displayed RT counts up to 100. Adds a new retweet_count_api field to tu_posts, now stores the value from Twitter in that and keeps track of the cached count from the posts in the database in 'retweet_count_cache'. 'old_retweet_count_cache' still counts the old-style retweets. What's displayed to the user is now 'old_retweet_count_cache' + the larger of 'retweet_count_cache' or 'retweet_count_api'. For posts collected prior to this fix, they will still display a count maxed out at Twitter's reporting threshold of 100.  Newly collected posts will show a more accurate RT count. The RTs listed (still) reflect the actual database contents. Closes #667, closes #813, closes #822

Other cases should be handled by specialntests.nCloses #1049n

Use timezone instead of UTC offset if possibleSet the time_zone session variable in MySQL to a timezone, e.g.nAmerica/Los_Angeles, instead of the current offset.  This fixesnconversion from/to UTC for times that are in a different offset.nnFor example, on 2011-10-28, Los Angeles is -07:00 because it is daylightnsaving time.  If you store 2011-01-01 00:00:00 into a TIMESTAMP fieldnwhen your time_zone session variable is set to '-07:00', the time willnbe stored as 2011-01-01 07:00:00 UTC instead of 2011-01-01 08:00:00,nwhich will be used if your time_zone variable is set ton'America/Los_Angeles'.nnUsing timezones instead of offsets requires that the MySQL timezonentables be populated.  See mysql_tzinfo_to_sql(1).  If a timezone can'tnbe used, fall back to using an offset.nnCloses #1073n

Fix working directory & table prefix assumptions in tests - Make paths to init.tests.php relative to __FILE__ so they don't make   assumptions about the working directory - Fix tests that assume the prefix is tu_ - Fix a few places that assume a trailing slash after directories - Restore the configuration file if it's moved out of the way during   testing and an exception occurs before it's moved back - Minor updates to tests/README.md - Remove /tests from THINKUP_BASE_URL THINKUP_BASE_URL was set to /tests when tests were run from the root directory.Make sure there's a slash between root dir and tests/viewnnAccept Access Denied as a correct failure on bad databasennWhen trying to install to a bad database name, the test assumed thatnaccess would be granted, and an Unknown database error would result.nIf access is denied, accept that as a correct failure as well.nnUse loopback for testing bad database hostnnWhen using a helpful DNS resolver that returns an IP address fornunresolvable hosts (see e.g. http://dns-opt-out.comcast.net/), using annunresolvable hostname like localcheese causes the test to hang whilenattempting to connect to port 3306 on an IP address that's droppingnpackets.nnInstead, we try to connect to a loopback address, 127.0.0.2, whichn(hopefully) isn't accessible so the connection is refused immediately.nnFix case of MySQL in class namesnnMore fixes for working directory & table prefix assumptions in testsnn- Make paths relative to __FILE__ so they don't make assumptions about then  working directoryn- Fix tests that assume the prefix is tu_n- Fix a few places that assume a trailing slash after directoriesnnFix for non-standard prefix that contains tu_nnUse #prefix# in query passed to newMigrationFilesnnCloses #187, closes #1089n

[DB MIGRATION REQ'D] Alert user about expired Facebook tokens As of July 5th, 2012, Facebook removed the offline_access permission. Instead, it automatically expires OAuth tokens after 60 days (for server-side apps like ThinkUp) and requires users to re-authorize to extend the application's rights for another 60 days. More info: https://developers.facebook.com/roadmap/offline-access-removal/ https://developers.facebook.com/docs/authentication/access-token-expiration/ https://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/2011/05/13/how-to--handle-expired-access-tokens/As of this commit, ThinkUp now:n* Tracks service authorization errors in the new tu_owner_instances.auth_error fieldn* Throws APIOAuthException when Facebook token is not valid during data capturen* Alerts user when Facebook OAuth tokens have expired via email and in an error message on the service user dashboardn* Does not crawl Facebook instances which have expired tokensn* Resumes data capture when user has re-authorized their accountnCloses #1349n

Fix upgrade.php --with-new-sql failures on source with database migrationsPrior to this commit, when a developer pulled the source code and there was a database migration since the last stable release, php upgrade --with-new-sql potentially failed because that migration was already published in build-db_mysql.sql, which was already run during installation.nnThis commit reverts build-db_mysql.sql to the latest version release, and creates a new script, build-db_mysql-upcoming-release.sql, which tests use. When the developer installs from source, s/he must also then run php upgrade --with-new-sql afterward, which will apply any pending migrations which have not gone out in a new user release.nnFrom now on, when a new user release gets packaged up, every change in the upcoming-release sql script will get rolled into build-db_mysql.sql.n

A link to a separate part of the documentation that tells developers how to run nightly codeThis page is presented in a way that fully explains how to get up an running as a ThinkUp developer. A problem I ran into was attempting to run code from HEAD in master where I could not figure out why my install was not working. Also the guide for what developers should do is currently on a page about upgrading while developers might hit the database migration issue on the initial install, not just on an upgrade.rnrnI think adding this link will at least attempt to direct developers in the correct direction.rnrnAn additional step might be highlighting Developers and Beta testers in the second level navigation under the Install menu option.

Facebook plugin: Handle business accountsIn the past, Facebook allowed business owners to sign up for an account withnno wall, profile, etc, that was just for managing pages and ads.nnThey no longer do so.  The /me api for these accounts does not returnna name field, which is sad, because we use that as the key in the instancesntable.nnFor reference, I found these stack overflow on this topic and the suggestionsnall come down to check for a name field:nhttp://stackoverflow.com/questions/14719211/how-can-i-know-if-a-facebook-account-is-personal-account-or-a-company-type-accounhttp://stackoverflow.com/questions/10857138/how-to-obtain-username-name-for-a-company-facebook-accountnnThis simply checks for a name parameter and then shows the user an error.n
